</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1158/2159-8290.CD-15-0235</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC4631646</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">26482930</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Xia Y., Ling A.L., Zhang W., Lee A., Su M.-C., Gruener R.F., Jena S., Huang Y., Pareek S., Shan Y., et al. A Web Application for Predicting Drug Combination Efficacy Using Monotherapy Data and IDACombo. J. Cancer Sci. Clin. Ther. 2024;7:253&#x2013;258. doi: 10.26502/jcsct.5079218.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.26502/jcsct.5079218</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC10852200</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">38344217</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Leek J.T., Johnson W.E., Parker H.S., Fertig E.J., Jaffe A.E., Zhangm Y., Storeym J.D., Torres L.C. sva: Surrogate Variable Analysis. R package version 3.56.0. 2025.  [(accessed on 14 October 2025)].  Available online:  https://bioconductor.org/packages/sva.</Citation></Reference><Reference><Citation>Galili T. Dendextend: An R Package for Visualizing, Adjusting and Comparing Trees of Hierarchical Clustering. Bioinformatics. 2015;31:3718&#x2013;3720. doi: 10.1093/bioinformatics/btv428.</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1093/bioinformatics/btv428</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pmc">PMC4817050</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">26209431</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="PubMed-not-MEDLINE" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41059291</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>08</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>10</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-eCollection"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">2234-943X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>15</Volume><PubDate><Year>2025</Year></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Frontiers in oncology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Front Oncol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Lower dose and weekly schedules of selinexor in multiple myeloma - updated evidence on safety and efficacy.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1649493</StartPage><MedlinePgn>1649493</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">1649493</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.3389/fonc.2025.1649493</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Selinexor, a first-in-class, oral exportin-1 inhibitor, showed activity in penta-refractory multiple myeloma (MM) in early trial exploration; however, the side-effect profile of twice-weekly dosing led to hesitant incorporation into widespread practice. Here, our objective is to provide updated clinical evidence highlighting the preserved efficacy and improved tolerability of once-weekly selinexor at lower doses in patients with previously treated MM compared to twice-weekly regimens.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Patient-level data from the BOSTON, STOMP, STORM, and XPORT-MM-028 clinical trials were systematically evaluated to elucidate relationships between selinexor dosing schedule, regimen toxicities, and efficacy in patients with MM that had progressed after at least one prior therapy.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">Updated results on once-weekly selinexor in combination with other anti-MM agents showed a reduced adverse event profile and improved tolerability compared with twice-weekly selinexor regimens, without compromise in efficacy. Furthermore, new data from several regimens with weekly selinexor delivery suggest that patients who had selinexor dose reductions or were treated in cohorts with a lower selinexor starting dose had reduced rates of adverse events, and superior durations of response. Weekly selinexor in combination with pomalidomide or carfilzomib in particular showed efficacy in difficult-to-treat, multiclass relapsed/refractory MM, including MM refractory to prior BCMA-directed therapies.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="UNASSIGNED">In a rapidly evolving field of previously treated MM, lowering of selinexor dose and frequency into weekly regimens showed a more feasible and tolerable treatment with continued efficacy when compared to twice-weekly schedules, paving the path for effective management of multiclass refractory MM, including patients with very advanced disease.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 Baljevic, Schiller, Mark, Van Domelen and Gasparetto.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Baljevic</LastName><ForeName>Muhamed</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Vanderbilt-Ingram Cancer Center, Vanderbilt University Medical Center, Nashville, TN,&#xa0;United States.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Schiller</LastName><ForeName>Gary</ForeName><Initials>G</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>David Geffen School of Medicine at University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA), Los Angeles, CA,&#xa0;United States.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Mark</LastName><ForeName>Tomer M</ForeName><Initials>TM</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Karyopharm Therapeutics Inc., Newton, MA,&#xa0;United States.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Van Domelen</LastName><ForeName>Dane R</ForeName><Initials>DR</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Karyopharm Therapeutics Inc., Newton, MA,&#xa0;United States.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Gasparetto</LastName><ForeName>Cristina</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Hematologic Malignancies and Cellular Therapy, Department of Medicine, Duke University Medical Center, Durham, NC,&#xa0;United States.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Aut